title: For Sale/Trade:  Hornady Steel Match .308 WIN 155gr BTHP (100 Rounds)
location: Smithfield/Clayton, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
I am clearing out the gun safe of a lot of stuff and this ammo is something I just don’t need. I have 100 rounds of this Hornady 155 Grain .308 Winchester Boat Tailed Hollow Point ammo in 50 round boxes. If you do not know what this ammo is… it is the super accurate 155 grain load from Hornady packed in a polymer coated steel case rather than brass. Before anyone sends an email… the bullet has no steel in it and is safe for your range but instead of brass cases Hornady used polymer covered steel as a cheaper alternative. This stuff is super accurate. The last few groups I fired with this stuff out of my Savage 110 LE with a 20” barrel were 0.75” to 0.83”. The round is the same one they load in their other match ammo but you are paying about 40% less because of the steel casing.

I paid $44.99 plus tax for each box at Fuquay Gun just last year. This stuff is not that easy to find and I am not looking to make any money on it so the first $90 get's both boxes. Lowball offers are not necessary. I am not in a hurry to sell it and will keep it before I give it away. It has been kept in a cool and dry ammo safe so this stuff is in the same condition as it was on the gun shop shelf.

If you are interested, I travel for a living across most of NC so if you want to meet and take a look at it please let me know and I’m sure we can work something out. Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  Lee Enfield No. 4 Mk II* (Savage 1941-1942)
postcontent:
I am looking to offer my Enfield No. 4 Mk II* in 303 Brit.  I bought this several years ago from an older gentleman that claims to have brought this home from England.  He was the US Air Force stationed in England after the war, and picked this up while he was there.  He claims it was an actual "war" rifle.  I do not know what year it was made, as I see different things on every forum, but if an 84C rifle was dated at mid 43 to early 44.....my 53C rifle should be late 41 to 42.....

I was given paperwork that was so thin, it was literally falling apart showing the import in the early 50's.  It has since faded into nothingness.......

So, now about the rifle.  This is a pretty good example of an early lend/lease Savage built Enfield stamped US PROPERTY.  There is a good amount of original green paint on the rifle.  Flip up rear sight, the rifling is still good and strong.  The bolt is smooth.  Matching serial numbers.  I have an old sling around here somewhere, and it does NOT have a magazine.  When I got it, he said that it was confiscated when he had it imported, and I do not believe that he ever shot it.  I have not shot it.  It is possible that this has not been shot since the 1940's.

I can only get so many pictures on here, but I have more if you want them.

I am open to working something out for this rifle.  I will be out of town starting Monday, 21 September, so I would like to try to work something out on Sunday, 20 September.

In its two forms, it was issued to both Union and Confederate troops in very limited quantities, the Maynard was the assault rifle of its day. Info
MAB PA-15 is a delayed blowback operated, semi-automatic pistol. It featured Savage-type, rotating, but not reciprocating, barrel, which has two lugs: one under the chambers is engaged in the frame and allows to the barrel to rotate but not to move back or forward. The other lug, on the upper surface of the barrel, is engaged in the curved-shaped notch inside the slide. When the pistol is fired, the barrel inertia and the bullet torque acted against the blowback force of the slide via the slope-shaped part of the notch. When bullet leaves the barrel, the slide rotates barrel and retracts to cycle the action. MAB PA-15 has a frame mounted safety, on the left side of the frame, and also internal magazine safety, which does not allow the gun to be fired with magazine removed.
